article.description:
Seimone Augustus is making her
first Southeastern Conference tournament look easy.
article.headline: Augustus scores 20 in second half for LSU
article.linkText: Freshman puts No. 5 LSU over the top in SEC semis
article.story:
NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Seimone Augustus is making her
first Southeastern Conference tournament look easy.

	   Augustus scored all 20 of her points in the second half,
including 12 in the final four minutes, to lead Louisiana State (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today; No. 6 Associated Press) to a
78-69 victory over Vanderbilt (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today; No. 15 Associated Press) in the semifinals of the SEC
tournament on Saturday night.

	   The freshman has scored 44 points in two games, including LSU's
last 14 points Saturday.

	   ''She was clutch,'' Vanderbilt center Chantelle Anderson said.
''She hit some big shots. She did a great job. She had a great
first step and pull up.''

	   Aiysha Smith had 21 points for LSU (26-3) but Augustus led the
comeback over the Commodores, who had eliminated LSU from the tournament the past three seasons.

	   In the first two games of the tournament, LSU avenged two of its
three defeats this season -- Arkansas and Vanderbilt. The Lady Tigers
will face No. 3 Tennessee, the only other team to beat LSU this
year, in the final Sunday. The Volunteers advanced with a 76-75
victory over Mississippi State.

	   Vanderbilt, which had 11 turnovers in the second half to LSU's
three, went almost six minutes without a basket after Jenni
Benningfield gave the Commodores (21-9) a 63-59 lead with 6:41 to
go.

	   ''We play a zone and they play a man,'' Vanderbilt coach Melanie
Balcomb said about the 18-6 difference in turnovers for the
game. ''They get in your face and press. It had more to do with
differences in philosophy than fatigue. They stepped up their
intensity in their man defense which is their strength.''

	   LSU capitalized on Vanderbilt's offensive drought by going on a
15-4 run, during which Augustus gave the Lady Tigers the lead for
good, 68-67, with a jumper in the lane. She made six free throws in
the final 1:35 and added two jumpers during LSU's spurt.

	   The Commodores' only basket in the final 6:41 was a jumper by
Abi Ramsey jumper with 45 seconds left. Anderson led Vanderbilt
with 24 points.

	   ''Nothing we've done with (Anderson) has worked,'' LSU coach Sue
Gunter said. ''She's just a load to handle if you ever get to that
low block.

	   ''We thought if we could work on the perimeter, if we could keep
her from having 35 or 40 points, we would have a chance to win.''

	   Augustus was 0-for-5 from the field in the first half, but she
was 6-for-8 and she made all eight of her free throws in the second.

	   ''My teammates kept me up at halftime,'' said Augustus, who had
nine rebounds. ''Coach made it very clear I had to go to the
boards. My teammates made up for me in the first half.''

	   Including the three tournament defeats, LSU had lost seven of
eight meetings to Vanderbilt since the 1999-2000 season.

	   LSU took its first lead at 44-43 with 17:18 left in the game on
a pair of free throws by Augustus. The Lady Tigers then began using
a full-court press after Vanderbilt point guard Ashley McElhiney
went to the bench briefly with an injury.

	   Balcomb said the Commodores should have built a bigger lead
while Augustus was struggling.

	   ''I don't think we would have been in that situation if we had
played defense,'' Balcomb said. ''We were late defensively for most
of the game.''

	   LSU pushed the lead to 49-45 on a three-point play by Temeka
Johnson with 15:49 left.

	   Benningfield, who finished with 17 points and 10 rebounds,
momentarily gave Vanderbilt the lead at 51-50, but LSU used another five-point spurt to take a 55-51 lead with 11:57
remaining.

	   Anderson hit two free throws and Benningfield scored to tie the
game at 55 before her basket gave Vanderbilt a 63-59 lead. Ramsey
missed a wide open 20-footer from the left wing for a seven-point
lead and Benningfield missed a 15-footer that would have cut LSU's
lead to three with 1:35 left.

	   ''We just weren't hitting our shots,'' Benningfield said. ''We
were just one step slow today and didn't hit our 3-point shots.''

	   Vanderbilt was 0-for-11 on 3-pointers in the second half after
making six of 12 in the first half.
